These files should be extracted into the same directory the 60-level
commercial version of Wolfenstein 3-D is located.  NO FILES WILL BE
OVERWRITTEN, NOT EVEN WHEN THE GAME'S GRAPHICS OR LEVELS ARE ALTERNATED.
Instead, the setup simply changes the names of the files ... nothing more.

     You can alternate the new levels with the original levels by entering
MAPS at the DOS prompt.  You have sixty new levels to enjoy.
     You can alternate the new graphics with the old by entering VSWAP.  The
new graphics have no new objects, but have several walls replaced:  Grey stone
walls are replaced with silver stone walls.  Blue dungeon walls are replaced
with semi-transparent blue stone walls.  The red bricks have a more
interesting texture, they're a little bit bigger, they have a couple more
"pictures" of mine, and have signs instead of Eagle Stickers;  I could put a
new german phrase in now, since I could use a German/English dictionary and
look up the German translation for "Stop!" (I ended up using a word that was
more like "Halt!", since "Halten!" looked better than "Stoppen!").  Steel
plated walls are replaced with green triangular walls.  I learned about
shading in Art Class and graphical textures by examining the original graphics
of Wolfenstein very closely.

     NOTE: To those who might ask me where I ray-traced the picture of the
potted flower (replacing the Eagle Statue wall image), no ray-tracing was used
in any of my new graphics!  I did all the graphics MYSELF.  Though I don't
mean to be vain, I just happen to be good at drawing plants.  I've only made
this note so I won't be hounded with this same question by endless amounts of
people, thank you very much.

     You can run the old maps with the new graphics and the old graphics with
the new maps.  Can't remember what levels and graphics that you have the game
set up to run?  Enter IDENTIFY.  It will tell you itself.

     You'll find a different set of saved games when you run my new levels.
The saved game titles you weren't responsible for I did myself.  I put them
there solely as a way for you to preview some of my favorite new levels, aside
from Level 1 of Episodes One, Five, and Six (my favorite new episode as a
whole is Two).  You needn't keep my saved games, so save over them as you
wish.  When you re-enable the original levels, you'll find your saved games
for the original levels are again available.

     Some of the original boards have pushwalls that can be pushed the wrong
way and cause you the loss of bonus items (or, in level 7 of Episode 4, the
loss of your key).  I avoid this approach entirely because I feel it just
simply isn't fun and is unfair to the player.

