     I hate to be telling you what you should and shouldn't do, but the latest
distribution policy requires me to ask this of you:  Please DON'T call Apogee
for any reason concerning these new boards.  Id isn't responsible for the new
boards' creation and doesn't support the levels in any way.  The batch files
will remind you of this.

The pre-saved games will send you to these areas:

"E2/L2": Episode 2, Level 2.  Starts off with a unusual pushwall trick and
then gets better.  Fun, fun, fun.  Hard, too!
"E2/L7": Episode 2, Level 7.  Like the original, you have the option of
finishing the level quickly or going through some hidden rooms for extra
points and extra challenge.  Unlike the original, though, I actually LIKE this
level.
"E2/L0": Episode 2, Level 10.  There's a booby-trap somewhere around in this
level.  Here's a hint to find the trap: "Fool's Gold".  There's a hidden
locked door and a hidden world as well.  Good hunting.
"E3/L0": Episode 3, Level 10.  Don't try to shoot these ghosts down;  they're
invincible!  Professionals may try getting all the points they can before
going to the elevator, but if you're anything less, it'll be all you can do
simply to get to the elevator in one piece!
"E3/L9": Episode 3, Level 9.  The Hitler board was never like this.
Threatening officers are placed in new scenarios and professional level
layout.  In the area with Hitler himself, most of the ammo is in a place where
you're exposed to the enemy in four different directions.  That secret with
the extra ammo is still around, accessed by pushing one of the walls with the
Hitler picture.  I ain't tellin' ya whar.
"E4/L3": Episode 4, Level 3.  Screw the original level (excuse my language) -
any one room from this level tops it all hands down!  But don't take my word
for it;  try the level out yourself.  Getting past this one is strictly trial
and error - it'll be easier for you when you know where you're going (though
it's still very challenging).  The largest hallway has several objects placed
near doors - use the objects to determine what room to go to when.  This board
challenges the player both physically and mentally.
"E5/L3": Episode 5, Level 3.  Big, big level is nothing like the original, but
you'll hardly mind.  The largest hallway has every turn marked in a specific
way - learning how to use the marks will make the journey much easier.
"E5/L0": Episode 5, Level 10.  There are two trails of treasure;  both lead to
an elevator, but each one leads to different scenarios.  This idea was
inspired by Blake Stone: Aliens of Gold.
"E6/L6": Episode 6, Level 6.  There are two pushwalls;  pushing either will
block your way to the other, but will allow you to proceed to the elevator.
Each pushwall takes you to different scenarios, but no matter which way you
go, the other side will eventually come back to haunt you!  There's a way to
get to the other side, but I'm not going to tell you how or where.
"E6/L8": Episode 6, Level 8.  This level has it all: a bit of treasure hidden
behind an object, visual spectacles, a pushwall shortcut, and movie-style
sequences.  There's also a pushwall you can push from one side to get more
ammo or from another side to get more health;  you get three chests of jewels
regardless of the direction you push.
